  "comment": "Parses Zig AST, extracts member signatures, and manages memory for the parser.",
  "detail": "# Module: src/guidance/ast_parser.zig\n\n## Module Purpose and Architecture\n\nThis module provides a structured interface to Zig's built-in AST parser, extracting semantic information about declarations (functions, variables, tests) from source code. It serves as the foundation for AI assistants that need to understand code structure, signatures, and documentation without requiring full compilation.\n\nThe architecture follows a **parser-visitor pattern** where `AstParser` holds the parsed tree state and provides methods to traverse it. Memory management is explicit: the parser requires an allocator and must be deallocated via `deinit()` to free AST resources.\n\n## Key Abstractions and Relationships\n\n1. **`AstParser`**: Main struct that encapsulates:\n   - Allocator for memory operations\n   - Source code slice being parsed\n   - Parsed AST tree (`std.zig.Ast`)\n\n2. **Member Extraction Pipeline**:\n   ```\n   Root Declarations → extractMember() → Specific Extractors\n     ↓\n   Functions    Variables       Tests\n     ↓              ↓               ↓\n   extractFunction  extractVarDecl  extractTest\n   ```\n\n3. **Dependencies**:\n   - `types.zig`: Defines `Member` struct and `MemberType` enum\n   - `hash.zig`: Generates signature hashes for matching\n   - `pattern.zig`: Detects code patterns in declarations\n\n## Public API and Usage Patterns\n\n### Initialization\n```zig\nconst parser = try AstParser.init(allocator, source);\ndefer parser.deinit();  // Critical: frees AST memory\n```\n\n### Core Operations\n- **`hasErrors()`**: Quick validation that parsing succeeded\n- **`extractMembers()`**: Primary entry point - returns owned slice of all extractable members\n- **`deinit()`**: Must be called to free internal AST resources\n\n### Typical Workflow\n1. Parse source with `AstParser.init()`\n2. Check errors with `hasErrors()`\n3. Extract members via `extractMembers()`\n4. Process member data (matching, analysis, etc.)\n5. Call `deinit()` when complete\n\n## Important Implementation Details\n\n- **Visibility Detection**: Public functions/variables have `visib_token != null`\n- **Test Filtering**: Functions starting with \"test\" are explicitly excluded from extraction\n- **Name Convention**: Variables starting with \"_\" are filtered out\n- **Hash Generation**: Each member gets a unique hash combining name, params, and return type for efficient matching\n- **Pattern Detection**: Uses `pattern.detectPatterns()` to identify common code patterns in declarations\n\n## Design Patterns Used\n\n1. **Resource Management Pattern**: Explicit allocator requirements with errdefer in extractors\n2. **Builder Pattern**: `extractMembers()` builds a list before returning owned slice\n3. **Strategy Pattern**: Different extractors (`extractFunction`, `extractVarDecl`, `extractTest`) handle different declaration types\n4. **Guard Clause Pattern**: Early returns on null/invalid states throughout",
  "keywords": ["AstParser", "extractMembers", "AST parsing", "Zig module analysis", "member extraction", "signature matching", "code pattern detection", "visibility tracking", "hash generation", "test filtering"],
